{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492922"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:50:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:50:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1187"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1187"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.39,0.02,0.31,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1187"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49588"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1187"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1187"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34859"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3390"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5865"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17702"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17736"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49588"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old woman with cholangitis secondary to choledocholithiasis undergoes an endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP), sphincterotomy and insertion of a stent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFour hours following the procedure the patient\u0027s condition deteriorates. She develops severe, constant abdominal pain in her right upper quadrant. Her blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse rate 110/min and temperature 38.2C. She is tender in the right upper quadrant with involuntary guarding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost-procedural bloods are taken and this reveals a mildly raised white cell count, and unchanged liver function tests.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for her deterioration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transient bacteraemia","Acute pancreatitis","Haemorrhage","Perforation","Blocked stent"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEvery procedure comes with its risks of complications. All those listed are potential complications of ERCP. Even in experienced hands the complication rate is about 10%. In this case, the onset of localised abdominal pain suggests peritoneal irritation and the possibility of \u003Cstrong\u003Eperforation\u003C/strong\u003E. Perforation may occur along the upper gastrointestinal tract where the endoscope is passed; at the level of the ampulla in the duodenum, where sphincterotomy is performed; or along the common bile duct and/or pancreatic duct, particularly when biliary dilatation is performed. If the sphincterotomy is misplaced or is too long, perforation may well occur. Perforation leads to biliary leakage, causing inflammation and potentially infection. This may manifest clinically as abdominal pain, fever and peritonitis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransient bacteraemia\u003C/strong\u003E may arise due to introduction of organisms into the vasculature at time of ERCP. However, this is typically not clinically significant, and in immunocompetent patients, rarely leads to sepsis. Persistent bacteraemia is a concern due to the potential for sepsis and spread of infection such as infective endocarditis and osteomyelitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E can arise following ERCP as a result of mechanical injury during duct manipulation and stent placement. This would typically present with epigastric pain, radiating through to the back and may be associated with nausea and vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhage \u003C/strong\u003Emay occur following ERCP as sphincterotomy involves cutting the Sphincter of Oddi. If this bleeds post-procedurally, there may be a haemoglobin drop, melaena, and hypotension which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocked stent: \u003C/strong\u003EIf the placed stent was blocked post-procedurally, this would present with progressive obstructive jaundice due to build-up of bilirubin. The relatively stable LFTs do not point towards a worsening blockage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Localising abdominal tenderness may suggest a perforation rather than other post-operative complications of ERCP."],"references":["Szary NM, Al-Kawas FH. Complications of Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography: How to Avoid and Manage Them. Gastroenterol Hepatol 2013; 9:496-504."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34859"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1187"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34859"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-31T21:35:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-31T21:38:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1187"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49588"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadin